{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 10:15:18.433662", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and context\n- Enterprise network with OSPF across core/distribution, access VLANs 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24, central server farm 10.200.0.0/24 hosting DNS, Apache web servers (web0.local…web3.local), and an Nginx HTTP load balancer (web99.local) that fronts backend web servers.\n- Objective: Assess current health, detect anomalies, localize faulty nodes, and identify root cause(s). No remediation provided.\n\nSummary of findings\n- Layer-3 reachability across the fabric is healthy: end-to-end ICMP works between hosts and server farm, with low latency and 0% loss.\n- DNS resolution is correct for web0–web3 and web99 on both hosts.\n- HTTP service availability:\n  - From host_1_1_1_1: HTTP to web99.local and web0–web3 succeeds with normal timing.\n  - From host_2_1_1_1: All HTTP attempts to any destination (web99.local, web0–web3, their IPs, and even itself) consistently fail with ~5-second timeouts.\n\nDetected anomalies\n- Host-specific HTTP failure on host_2_1_1_1 only, despite good IP reachability and correct DNS.\n- The failure is protocol/port-specific (TCP/80), not network-path or name-resolution related.\n\nFault localization\n- Fault localized to the endpoint host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10).\n- Network infrastructure elements (distribution/core routers, server_access_router), DNS server, load balancer, and web servers show no blocking or service-side issues.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Evidence shows host_2_1_1_1 is locally filtering TCP port 80 in both directions:\n  - nftables ruleset on host_2_1_1_1:\n    - table inet filter:\n      - chain input: tcp dport 80 drop\n      - chain forward: tcp dport 80 drop\n      - chain output: tcp dport 80 drop\n  - This explains why:\n    - curl from host_2_1_1_1 to any HTTP endpoint shows connect/starttransfer at 0 with total ≈ 5.00 s (connection timeout).\n    - curl to its own IP also fails (both outbound and inbound port 80 are dropped).\n- Contrasting evidence on other nodes:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 has no such drop rule; HTTP succeeds.\n  - server_access_router, load_balancer, and web_server_0–3 iptables policies are ACCEPT with no blocking rules.\n  - Services listen on port 80: netstat shows 0.0.0.0:80 listening on load_balancer and all web_server_{0..3}.\n\nDetailed evidence\n- Reachability (ICMP):\n  - Pings among hosts and between hosts and server farm succeed; example: host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer 0% loss, ~3.56 ms avg; web servers -> host_2_1_1_1 also OK.\n- DNS correctness:\n  - getent on both hosts resolves:\n    - web99.local -> 10.200.0.7\n    - web0.local -> 10.200.0.3\n    - web1.local -> 10.200.0.4\n    - web2.local -> 10.200.0.5\n    - web3.local -> 10.200.0.6\n- HTTP from host_1_1_1_1 (normal):\n  - curl http://web99.local x3: name lookup ~3–9 ms; connect ~5–15 ms; starttransfer ~0.25–0.31 s; total ~1.05–1.11 s.\n  - curl http://web{0..3}.local x2 each: similar healthy metrics; total ~1.03–1.13 s.\n- HTTP from host_2_1_1_1 (failing):\n  - curl to web99.local, web0–web3, and their IPs, plus to 10.1.1.10 and 10.2.1.10: namelookup ~3–9 ms; connect/starttransfer 0.000; total ~5.001 s (timeout) consistently.\n- Host_2 firewall:\n  - nft list ruleset shows explicit drops for tcp dport 80 in input, forward, and output chains (policy accept otherwise).\n- Infrastructure ACLs/firewalls:\n  - server_access_router iptables: INPUT/FORWARD/OUTPUT ACCEPT.\n  - router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, router_core_2, router_core_3: INPUT/FORWARD/OUTPUT ACCEPT.\n  - load_balancer and web_server_0–3 iptables ACCEPT; services listening on TCP/80.\n\nAssessment of overall health\n- Underlay/OSPF routing: Operational, inferred by successful cross-subnet ICMP and DNS/HTTP success from host_1_1_1_1 to server farm.\n- Server farm: DNS and HTTP services available; load balancer listening; backend policy not evaluated here, but no reachability problems observed.\n- Access segment 10.2.1.0/24: IP/DHCP normal (host_2_1_1_1 has dynamic lease and proper default route); the only issue is a local host firewall policy.\n- End-user experience:\n  - Host_1_1_1_1: Normal access to web services.\n  - Host_2_1_1_1: Unable to use HTTP due to local TCP/80 filtering.\n\nConclusion\n- Anomaly: HTTP connectivity failure isolated to host_2_1_1_1.\n- Faulty device: host_2_1_1_1.\n- Root cause: nftables filter rules on host_2_1_1_1 dropping TCP traffic with destination port 80 (input/forward/output), causing consistent HTTP timeouts despite normal IP reachability and correct DNS.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10661, "output_tokens": 3601, "total_tokens": 14262, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9088}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2304}}}
